snippet.textDisplay: I think the photo composition and main subject have a bigger influence than you may think. A good photographer would be able to spot the most interesting or beautiful thing in a particular scene, or even shot it in a way that make it so. Just because you make a thing the main subject of a photo doesn't mean people want to look at it. If the most interesting thing is in the background and the ”High quality” camera blurs it out, people can feel irritated. A good photo can be taken by a disposable camera, and a high end camera can take shit photos too.

snippet.textDisplay:
If I could try to explain why the people went for pictures with more detail in focus instead of the "high quality" photos:


the palette of colours is very saturated, so it attracts my attention. As such, it could count as a subject, even though the photographer doesn't intend for it to be. Therefore, when you only put your subject into focus and have everything else be a blurred background, you're forcing my eyes to look somewhere they don't want to look, which ends up being annoying.


In other words, enthusiast photographers love to only put their intended subject into focus to make people look where they want. On the other hand, people hate being forced to look at one thing in a photo.

snippet.textDisplay:
As a statistician this experiment makes me feel violated in a very bad way.

1. It’s not correct to compare just two phones in one round and not compare them later with others
2. One photo does not define the real quality of shots (iPhone example)
3. You don’t give us numbers on the your sample quality (age, gender and etc. ) maybe the choices change with age and gender.
4. You were taking photos in uncontrolled environment (not using tripods, outside where lights are not stable, and clouds are moving, thus changing a background)
5. Did you control for battery life? It’s known that phone performance isn’t linear, hence, depends on level of battery change.

I can keep on going. But the real thing is you just shouldn’t drive conclusions based on data you have, especially when 10 million people may watch it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Regarding MKBHD's assertion that people chose photos based on how focused the photos are (even though less focus on the background means the sensors are better and are nicer), I have a question. Are the modes for camera in portrait mode? If not then indeed, photos with everything in focus is more desired.

Say I want to take a scenery shot with me in it, and the camera does auto-portrait mode, that would ruin the scenery shot I'm trying to take. So it's pretty funny how MKBHD thinks this way. Plus nowadays there are some cameras that auto-add beauty mode, which can be irritating as well.
